  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering and Financial Crimes Strategy Act\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. State Laws:\nMany states also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Criminalize the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Create reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to help law enforcement track financial crimes.\n\nPenalties can be severe, potentially including significant prison sentences and substantial financial penalties.",
